<HEADLINE>
<P>
OUTTAKES: FULL THROTTLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Pat H. Broeske and Elaine Dutka 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Paramount Pictures has turned up the boost on its "Days of Thunder" promotional 
blitz by enticing several automotive and racing publications to cover the Tom 
Cruise race-car drama as it closes in on its June 27 opening. 
</P>
<P>
The trade journal AutoWeek is on the stands with a cover story titled "Box 
Office Thunder" and upcoming issues of Motor Trend and Circle Track have inside 
pieces on the movie. 
</P>
<P>
More coverage is coming in automotive sections in dozens of newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
Joseph Molina, the Woodland Hills-based automotive PR specialist brought in to 
coordinate special "Thunder" publicity, is pushing the film's "revolutionary" 
racing footage and the Chevy Lumina that Cruise drives in the picture. He tells 
us that Paramount's put a quartet of Lumina racers "on tour." 
</P>
<P>
The automotive articles, however, will suffer from Cruise Control. 
</P>
<P>
"We heard about what a terrific driver he is -- but couldn't get any access to 
him," says Auto-Week executive editor Kevin Wilson. At the studio's request, 
the magazine sent written questions to Cruise, but "the answers were really 
soft" -- and got scrapped. With a nod to "Thunder" spreads in current issues of 
Sports Illustrated and Life, Wilson muses, "They got lots and lots of access. 
If I'd known we weren't, I might not have committed to the cover." Pat H. 
Broeske and Elaine Dutka 
</P>
</TEXT>
