<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALBUM REVIEW; 
</P>
<P>
**** BOBBY WATSON AND HORIZON "THE INVENTOR" BLUE NOTE: ALBUMS ARE RATED FROM 
FIVE STARS (A CLASSIC) TO ONE STAR (POOR). 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BILL KOHLHAASE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A veteran of Art Blakey's Jazz Messengers and the respected 29th St. Saxophone 
Quartet, alto saxophonist Bobby Watson shows all the right influences -- Johnny 
Hodges, Sonny Stitt and, of course, Charlie Parker -- but doesn't rely on 
imitation to get his point across. Tunes such as his sophisticated ballad 
"Dreams So Real," the smoothly-paced "Homemade Blues" and "Heckle and Jeckle," 
on which Watson trades bird calls with trumpeter Melton Mustafa, put a 
contemporary shine on the hard bop tradition and provide a framework for some 
strong emotional expression. Drummer Victor Lewis also contributes two numbers, 
including "The Shaw of Newark," a spirited tribute to the late trumpeter Woody 
Shaw. BILL KOHLHAASE 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Recording Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
