<HEADLINE>
<P>
READ THEIR LETTERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I find it interesting that the letters defending New Kids on the Block ("Oh, 
You Kids," June 10) appeared on the same day as the article in which their 
manager admitted that New Kids sometimes lip-sync during their concerts. 
</P>
<P>
The way I see it, New Kids are cleverly promoted entertainers rather than 
musicians with any sort of artistic integrity. 
</P>
<P>
I hardly think their new album merits a five-star rating (as Michelle Parkinson 
suggested in her letter), unless we're giving points for unadulterated 
commercialism. 
</P>
<P>
As for the adults that go to New Kids' concerts with their children, one 
wonders how many parents are there involuntarily simply because most of New 
Kids' fans are too young to go to concerts unattended. Chris Willman's negative 
review of "Step by Step" certainly won't stop it from selling millions of 
copies, but the fact is that, as musicians, New Kids on the Block are great 
dancers. 
</P>
<P>
MELISSA HENRY 
</P>
<P>
Garden Grove 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA061790-0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 234631 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
June 17, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Page 95; Calendar Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
199 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
READ THEIR LETTERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Live, in media land, means real. It means what the audience member sees and 
hears in concerts is what is happening right there and then -- not what 
happened in the studio six months ago. 
</P>
<P>
For a concertgoer, it means that the interaction between the person on the 
stage and the audience is genuine, not contrived, not premeditated. 
</P>
<P>
Backing vocals are the antithesis of what a "live concert" is supposed to be 
about. As a consumer, I already paid upward of $10 for the album or cassette 
that made me think the performer was worth going to see live. If Headlee thinks 
I am not being hoodwinked by having to pay upwards of $25 to hear that exact 
same music at a so-called "live concert," he is only demonstrating his own lack 
of integrity. 
</P>
<P>
Real artists, the people I pay to see perform, would never give me anything 
less than authenticity. When is the last time Sting, U2, Prince or 10,000 
Maniacs used any kind of backing vocals or taped instrumentation? Tina Turner, 
Paul McCartney and David Bowie are old (in rock 'n' roll terms, of course) and 
their voices aren't all of what they once were, but when you see and hear them 
in concert it is truly them. 
</P>
<P>
ADREANA LANGSTON 
</P>
<P>
Long Beach 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA061790-0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 234632 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
June 17, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Page 95; Calendar Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
