<P>
THE CHURCH'S VIEWS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Can it be that the Catholic Church has its left foot in its mouth and the right 
foot doesn't know? View on June 6 makes one wonder. The reporting of two rites 
of passage -- the Latino quinceanera and high society's coming out -- reflects 
opposing church attitudes. 
</P>
<P>
We read that the Archdiocese of Los Angeles has issued new guidelines for 
quinceaneras to simplify a tradition that has ". . . become too secular, too 
social and too costly" ("Is the Party Over?" Page 1). 
</P>
<P>
On another page of the same issue, we read that in a ballroom of the Beverly 
Hilton Hotel there was "no shortage of pomp" as this year's designer-clad 
(Social Services Auxiliary) debutantes were presented to the Archbishop of Los 
Angeles ("On View"). 
</P>
<P>
If there is an award for ambivalence, I hereby nominate the Catholic Church. 
</P>
<P>
LEA PETRICK 
