1475 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
OXNARD FACES HARD CHOICES IN TRIMMING $2.8 MILLION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By HUGO MARTIN, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For the last three years, Oxnard has been able to use reserve funds to fend off 
a government administrator's most dreaded foe: a deficit. 
</P>
<P>
But the fiend has returned with a price tag of $2.8 million, and officials for 
the city -- operating on an annual budget of $61.7 million -- have vowed not to 
touch its reserves, which have dwindled to a dangerously low level. 
</P>
<P>
As the city begins to discuss ways to chop the deficit, many residents fear 
that, without the use of reserve funds, the hungry deficit will eat away at 
city services such as police and fire protection. 
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, voters overwhelmingly rejected a 5% utility-tax increase 
that city officials had hoped would solve the city's financial crisis by 
generating $5 million annually. The loss at the polls came despite a $40,000 
publicity campaign for the measure, funded primarily by developers and city 
employee groups. 
</P>
<P>
City officials have said service and personnel cuts are now inevitable. The 
City Council began meeting last week to discuss which cuts to make and how deep 
to make them. But council members decided to delay final decisions until 
Tuesday, when the results of a long-awaited management audit are to be 
released. 
</P>
<P>
In an effort to balance the budget for the fiscal year beginning July 1, City 
Manager David Mora has compiled a list of 64 personnel cuts -- including 16 in 
the Police Department and eight in the Fire Department. 
</P>
<P>
An early target for cuts, the Colonia Youth Boxing Gym was taken off Mora's 
cost-cutting list last month after several Latino parents urged the council to 
spare the gym, which costs the city about $44,000 a year and serves about 50 
boys a day. 
</P>
<P>
While some city officials have characterized the city's fiscal situation as a 
full-blown crisis, others are more optimistic. "This is not the end of the 
world, and we are acting like it is," Councilwoman Dorothy Maron said at the 
beginning of last week's budget hearings. 
</P>
<P>
This year's deficit is primarily the result of several unexpected expenditures, 
including a $690,000 increase in the cost for workers compensation and $460,000 
to remove asbestos from city buildings, Mora said. 
</P>
<P>
"If we didn't have these new elements, we'd be balanced," Mora said. 
</P>
<P>
Management and Budget Director Bill Mayer said Oxnard's long-term budget 
problems have developed because of a series of revenue losses beginning in 
1986. 
</P>
<P>
For example, that year the federal government ended a revenue-sharing program 
that generated $2.2 million a year for Oxnard. The same year, the city lost an 
additional $1.5 million because of reduced franchise taxes paid by Southern 
California Gas Co. 
</P>
<P>
In 1987, the city lost $2.1 million when the City Council eliminated a 2% 
utility tax two years before it was scheduled to expire. 
</P>
<P>
The following year, Oxnard began losing $600,000 annually when fines from 
convicted drunk drivers began to be diverted from the city to the county. 
</P>
<P>
However, Mayer said the city is beginning to see increased sales-tax revenue 
generated from several new businesses, such as the Price Club, Home Depot and 
the Oxnard Auto Mall, all of which opened recently near the Pacific Coast and 
Ventura freeways. 
</P>
<P>
He said the city is expecting increased sales and property taxes from several 
new developments -- including the 450,000-square-foot Plaza del Norte shopping 
center, to be completed in September, and the 4.4-million-square-foot Town 
Center business park and shopping mall, to be completed within 15 years. 
</P>
<P>
The developments "have the potential to ease the problems that we have," Mayer 
said. 
</P>
<P>
Still, revenue from such new developments are not expected to solve this year's 
budget crisis, and city officials say Oxnard residents are just going to have 
to tighten their belts. 
</P>
<P>
The Police Department would suffer the biggest financial loss -- $795,000 a 
year -- under Mora's plan. Mora has suggested that the city eliminate 16 
positions, including six motorcycle traffic officers, a youth-services officer 
and a victim-assistance specialist. Anticipating such cuts, the department has 
left vacant four positions on the city's drunk-driving task force. Mora has 
suggested that the unit be eliminated. 
</P>
<P>
The 154-officer department already has eight vacancies. If the recommended cuts 
are made, those jobs would remain unfilled and eight more would be eliminated 
through attrition, city officials have said. 
</P>
<P>
Police Chief Robert Owens told the council last week that the recommended cuts 
would hurt the department's ability to protect residents. "I don't want to give 
up anything," he said. 
</P>
<P>
Owens told the council that the victim-assistance specialist works as a trained 
counselor for victims of rape and child abuse. The youth-services officer acts 
as a liaison to the city's elementary and junior high schools, he said. He also 
warned that, when the city eliminated the motorcycle traffic team in 1978, the 
number of traffic deaths in Oxnard jumped. 
</P>
<P>
Since August, when the drunk-driving enforcement team was eliminated, the 
Police Department has arrested 495 fewer motorists than during the same period 
a year earlier, when 1,690 were taken in, police said. 
</P>
<P>
Last month, dozens of police officers and firefighters tried to eliminate the 
need for personnel cuts by campaigning door-to-door in support of the 5% 
utility-tax increase. 
</P>
<P>
In an effort to save money, Councilwoman Ann Johs suggested last week that the 
county be asked to take over the police and fire protection in Oxnard. The 
council is scheduled to discuss the proposal on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
The Parks and Recreation Department would suffer the largest personnel losses 
under Mora's plan. 
</P>
<P>
The city manager has recommended the elimination of 17 positions there, 
including two landscape workers, a park ranger and nine custodians. Mora 
suggested that the city contract with a private firm to take over the city's 
custodial services. 
</P>
<P>
Mora has also suggested that the city close several buildings operated by the 
department on Sundays and eliminate the Junior High Grad Night Program. The 
city now spends $19,400 to supervise and transport almost 1,000 graduating 
junior high school students each year to a local amusement park. 
</P>
<P>
The city can save $478,000 by implementing these cuts. 
</P>
<P>
The loudest outcry from residents was prompted by Mora's recommendation to 
close the Carnegie Art Museum, which would save the city $140,000 a year. 
</P>
<P>
Mona Broyles, chairwoman of the Oxnard Cultural and Fine Arts Commission, 
called the proposed closure "totally unacceptable." She has urged the council 
to "please seek another alternative cutback." Once the museum is closed, 
Broyles said, it will be almost impossible to persuade other museums to loan 
art exhibits to the Carnegie in the future. 
</P>
<P>
Museum Director Andrew Voth said closure could permanently ruin the city's 
reputation in the art world. Just the rumor that the Carnegie will close has 
lost the museum $20,000 in grants, he said. "It's devastating." 
</P>
<P>
The 10,000-square-foot museum, which houses a permanent collection of 250 
paintings and sculptures, opened in 1981 and has a staff of one part-time and 
three full-time employees. 
</P>
<P>
Mora has proposed that the city save $343,500 by eliminating two emergency 
rescue squads and eight firefighters. 
</P>
<P>
The emergency vehicles, each staffed by four full-time firefighters, carry 
emergency tools -- such as the "Jaws of Life" -- to the scene of a fire or 
accident. 
</P>
<P>
The Fire Department has 43 firefighters and seven vacancies. 
</P>
<P>
Fire Chief Richard Smith told the council last week that there are 22 
firefighters on duty at all times. He warned that elimination of the two squads 
would reduce fire service by 9%. 
</P>
<P>
Smith said the department normally dispatches 12 firefighters to battle a 
routine single-family house fire, leaving 10 firefighters to monitor the rest 
of the city. 
</P>
<P>
"It's a little bit frightening, frankly," he said of the proposed cuts. 
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that the city has a mutual-assistance agreement with fire 
departments from nearby cities. 
</P>
<P>
Mora has suggested that the city close its main library on Sundays to save 
$11,000 in overtime salaries, which would entail no personnel cuts. 
</P>
<P>
The city manager has also recommended that the city eliminate its $398,000 
contribution to the Oxnard Convention and Visitors Bureau, which employs six 
full-time staff members. 
</P>
<P>
Robert D. Varley, executive chairman of the bureau, said elimination of the 
city contribution would force closure of the bureau. He said the elimination 
would have a devastating effect on tax revenue generated by hotels and by other 
tourism-related businesses. 
</P>
<P>
Mora also suggested that the city save $200,000 by eliminating three employees 
from the city's street-sweeping unit. City officials said such a reduction 
would mean that the average residential street would be swept every three 
months, while streets in business districts would be swept twice a month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Proposed budget cuts could affect recreation areas such as Colonia Park, 
left, ; Photo, and the public library, right, which would close Sundays. ALAN 
HAGMAN / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
