1812 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ENVIRONMENTALISTS LOOK TOWARD CITY RACES; 
</P>
<P>
POLITICS: TWO UNEXPECTED VICTORIES HAVE GIVEN SLOW-GROWTH BACKERS HOPE THAT 
VOTERS ARE READY TO LIMIT DEVELOPMENT. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DARYL KELLEY, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Unexpected victories by slow-growth advocates in three Ventura City Council 
races and in a county supervisor race have convinced environmentalists that the 
greening of politics has begun in Ventura County. 
</P>
<P>
"I would suggest that anybody running on a strictly environmental platform can 
get into office if they are credible," said Stan Greene, president of the 
700-member group Citizens to Preserve the Ojai. "There is a groundswell now. I 
think the last two elections bear that out." 
</P>
<P>
Some environmentalists are already looking to elections in November, when they 
expect numerous candidates to run for City Council seats in attempts to slow 
Oxnard's rapid growth and to curb what they see as development abuses in 
Camarillo and Thousand Oaks. 
</P>
<P>
Indeed, with the astounding upset victory by 25-year-old political novice Maria 
VanderKolk for 2nd District supervisor on June 5, slow-growth advocates say 
they see unparalleled political possibilities. 
</P>
<P>
"This is our window of opportunity," said Ken Bauer of Westlake Village, a key 
strategist in VanderKolk's victory over Supervisor Madge L. Schaefer. 
</P>
<P>
VanderKolk's success -- attributed to her opposition to two large housing 
projects and to Schaefer's refusal to seriously campaign -- also reflects the 
impact of canvassing by about 75 volunteers recruited primarily from the 
fledgling environmental group Save Open Space. 
</P>
<P>
That type of shoe-leather support by volunteers also marked the victories last 
fall of new Ventura City Council members Cathy Bean, Gary Tuttle and Todd 
Collart, who argued that city limits on growth were too lax. 
</P>
<P>
"VanderKolk's victory underscores the point that you can't get elected in this 
area without seriously addressing the issue of growth," said Kevin Sweeney, 
public-affairs director for Ventura-based Patagonia Inc., a clothing company 
that contributes to environmental groups and local campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
"There has been a victory in the north part of the county and a victory in the 
south part," he said, "so now you begin to fill in the blanks in between." 
</P>
<P>
How that can be done is uncertain. But it appears that several slow-growth 
candidates will run in Oxnard this fall, when a majority of the five positions 
on the City Council will be on the ballot. 
</P>
<P>
Though filing does not begin until mid-July, Paul K. Dolan and Scott Bollinger 
have already announced their candidacies, citing "unequivocal opposition to 
future rampant growth" as part of their joint platform. 
</P>
<P>
Accountant Scott Weiss, who co-founded a slow-growth group early this year, 
said last week that the VanderKolk upset had encouraged him to consider running 
for the Oxnard council. 
</P>
<P>
Weiss said his small organization is looking for other slow-growth candidates 
to back and is soliciting help from Patagonia, which provided financial backing 
and advice to VanderKolk and to the three Ventura candidates. 
</P>
<P>
In Camarillo, representatives from five homeowner groups are meeting to decide 
how to fight zoning changes that are allowing agricultural land to be developed 
as shopping centers and industrial parks, homeowner Chris DeSales said last 
week. 
</P>
<P>
He expects an umbrella organization to be formed soon that will back City 
Council candidates in the fall campaign, said DeSales, a resident of Woodside 
Greens at the base of the Conejo Grade. 
</P>
<P>
"It's the same issue with each group," he said. "People are seeing more 
agricultural land going under. We are all concerned about this kind of 
development, which seems to be continuing unabated." 
</P>
<P>
In Thousand Oaks, some supporters of VanderKolk say they hope to continue their 
crusade for stringent growth controls in City Council races there. Thousand 
Oaks, under Measure A passed in 1980, limits residential construction to 500 
units a year -- a sharp cut from the thousands per year proposed before its 
approval. 
</P>
<P>
But Eloise Zeanah, campaign manager for VanderKolk and twice an unsuccessful 
council candidate, said she and others are bothered by the City Council's 
borrowing of housing allocations from future years. 
</P>
<P>
"The residents need to know that our elected officials have skirted the intent 
of Measure A," she said. "It has not controlled growth, it has only metered it. 
These problems are beginning to surface now." 
</P>
<P>
Despite the environmentalists' surge of optimism since the recent victories, 
some slow-growth advocates have begun to discuss how they can push their 
message more effectively. 
</P>
<P>
Sweeney, Bauer and others said that, if Ventura County environmental groups -- 
traditionally linked loosely and only marginally active in politics -- are to 
take advantage of voters' heightened concerns, a countywide environmental 
organization needs to be established. 
</P>
<P>
"If we are going to prevent Ventura County from becoming another Orange County, 
we really do need to get better organized," said Bauer, an ARCO executive who 
moved from Los Angeles in 1976 to escape crime and congestion. "I'd love to get 
something more permanent set up." 
</P>
<P>
Sweeney said the current race-by-race approach to politics is not the best way 
to win elections. In addition, it provides little research to support the 
positions of slow-growth candidates once they are elected and "have to say no 
to development 400 to 500 times in four years," he said. 
</P>
<P>
"The next stage that has to happen will be a more proactive environmental 
organization," Sweeney said. Such an office, staffed with a full-time 
environmental researcher, would mean that "this county begins to develop a 
backbone around its environment," he said. 
</P>
<P>
A model for that organization can be found 30 miles up the U.S. 101 in Santa 
Barbara County, where a strong push since a disastrous 1969 oil spill has led 
to a network of environmental organizations. 
</P>
<P>
The groups include an agency to monitor neighborhood growth issues, a political 
action committee, a large research institute and a legal center with three 
attorneys. 
</P>
<P>
Slow-growth advocates, assisted by this network, now hold a majority of the 
seats on the Santa Barbara City Council and the County Board of Supervisors, 
said Robert Klausner, head of the political-action committee. 
</P>
<P>
"This issue is a slam dunk," Klausner said. "We haven't had to sell anything. 
It's tapping on concerns about the quality of life. It's not like someone is 
laying a philosophy on them." 
</P>
<P>
In Ventura County, individual environmental groups have scored a number of 
legal and political victories during the last 20 years, but no such network has 
ever been formed. 
</P>
<P>
Patagonia recently has filled the role of a countywide environmental agency, 
contributing $35,000 to local organizations last fiscal year and offering 
political support in three campaigns, beginning with an unsuccessful 
congressional bid in 1988 by state Sen. Gary K. Hart (D-Santa Barbara). 
</P>
<P>
The outdoor-clothing company, whose influence has grown as its sales have 
boomed since 1984, contributed $15,000 in slow-growth advertisements to last 
fall's city races and $9,000 in ads leading up to this month's supervisorial 
election. Owners Yvon and Malinda Chouinard contributed $2,000 personally to 
VanderKolk, the maximum allowed by law. 
</P>
<P>
"In a lot of ways, we've been a deep pockets for this county," said Sweeney, 
who has orchestrated the company's move into political activism since he 
arrived two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
Patagonia has also hired part time the pre-eminent environmental researcher in 
the county, Russ Baggerly, a former shoemaker from Meiners Oaks who for years 
was a spokesman for both Citizens to Preserve the Ojai and the Environmental 
Coalition. 
</P>
<P>
Baggerly and his wife, Pat, are still directors of the Environmental Coalition, 
a loose-knit group that takes positions on countywide issues and claims about 
400 members. 
</P>
<P>
Several directors of the Environmental Coalition said in interviews that they 
too would like to see a more coherent countywide approach to environmental 
problems but see no obvious way to achieve that goal. 
</P>
<P>
"For 10 years now, I've been told that there are two things I have to do -- go 
out and get volunteers and get people elected to office. I'm absolutely 
worthless at both," said Cynthia Leake, a coalition director and chairwoman of 
the 1,800-member Sespe Group of the Los Padres Chapter of the Sierra Club. 
</P>
<P>
To create a political arm "takes money, time and energy. We need a staff and 
don't have one," she said. 
</P>
<P>
Russ Baggerly said that while local environmentalists want more support for 
both research and political campaigns, they haven't come to expect it. 
</P>
<P>
"We'll probably take it a race at a time," he said. "We know we have to get 
environmentally sensitive people elected to office. But it comes down to 
money." And neither staunch environmentalists nor residents who simply want to 
slow the pace of growth seem to contribute much to such campaigns, he said. 
</P>
<P>
Neil Moyer, president of the coalition and a new member of the Ventura Planning 
Commission, said there are other basic problems with the concept of a 
countywide environmental group. 
</P>
<P>
"Different groups have different objectives, and they don't always overlap," 
said Moyer, an air-quality expert who works for Texaco. 
</P>
<P>
In addition, the east and west counties, separated by the Conejo Grade, are 
geographically distinct and have different problems, as do the inland areas 
near Ojai and Fillmore, he said. 
</P>
<P>
"So things are still very much fragmented on both a geographical basis and on 
an issues basis," he said. "That's always going to be a problem with 
environmental groups. Though they all arguably are under this green umbrella, 
they have different interests and some of them are not very political at all." 
</P>
<P>
Ventura Councilman Gary Tuttle, a former world-class runner elected on a 
slow-growth platform last fall, said: "I think the environmental movement is 
here to stay. 
</P>
<P>
"But I'm not going to go out and try to organize the county. I'm staying in 
Ventura. I've got enough problems right here." 
</P>
<P>
Ventura County's desire to hold back the sprawl of Los Angeles County has been 
apparent for at least three decades, veterans of the environmental movement 
say. 
</P>
<P>
Citizens to Preserve the Ojai, formed in the mid-1960s, blocked an effort to 
widen California 33, which would have allowed a growth boom. 
</P>
<P>
In 1970, Pat Ellison, fresh from cleaning sea birds soiled with oil from the 
Santa Barbara slick, helped found the Environmental Coalition. And in 1973, she 
joined two other slow-growth candidates on the Ventura City Council. 
</P>
<P>
With John McWherter, who is still on the council, they approved a series of 
pioneering reforms that created an agricultural preserve within the city and 
forced the clustering of new construction closer to the city. 
</P>
<P>
Ventura County also approved a General Plan that requires development to be 
clustered in or near cities. Now, all 10 cities in the county, except for 
Oxnard, limit construction in some way. 
</P>
<P>
"We've had a lot of victories over the last 20 years, but we're still 
struggling hard," Ellison said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Kevin Sweeney is public affairs director for Patagonia Inc., a Ventura 
clothing company that backs campaigns of slow-growth advocates. LAWRENCE K. HO 
/ Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA061790-0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 234794 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
June 17, 1990, Sunday, Ventura County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 1; Column 2 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
725 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SIX IS NOT ENOUGH; 
</P>
<P>
FATHERHOOD: KEVIN KOLBECK LOVES HAVING A BIG FAMILY. HE SAYS DISCIPLINE -- AND 
A SUPPORTIVE WIFE -- ARE ESSENTIAL. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GARY GORMAN, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With six children and another on the way, Kevin Kolbeck has a big family by 
today's standards. 
</P>
<P>
According to state figures, the average household in Ventura County has only 
3.006 people. 
</P>
<P>
But Kevin Kolbeck hasn't finished with fatherhood. By the time he and his wife, 
Michelle, are through, they may well raise that statistic by a thousandth or 
two. 
</P>
<P>
"We're not shooting for any particular number, but 12 is not out of the 
question," Kolbeck said. "I tell people we want to have a birthday each month 
of the year." 
</P>
<P>
On Father's Day, many dads savor the unique satisfaction of creating and 
nurturing a child. For Kevin Kolbeck, there is also the satisfaction of 
accomplishing his life's goal. 
</P>
<P>
"When I was growing up, I just loved family life," Kolbeck said. "I couldn't 
wait to have my own and do the same things my parents and sisters and I did 
together." 
</P>
<P>
The Kolbecks, who live in Santa Paula, do just about everything together. 
</P>
<P>
"I hate not having the kids involved in what we're doing," Kolbeck said. "We 
rarely do things apart." 
</P>
<P>
That means taking two cars to the drive-in movies, as the family did the other 
night -- one for any little Kolbecks who fell asleep. 
</P>
<P>
It means bringing the whole brood when Kevin competes in his men's basketball 
league, when Michelle Kolbeck goes shopping, when the family attends Sacred 
Heart Catholic Church in Ventura. 
</P>
<P>
Above all, Kevin said, it means discipline. 
</P>
<P>
"I think that's the key to success in a big family, having kids who behave," he 
said. "Then you're not afraid to take them places. You can sit and have an 
enjoyable meal as a family. Even with six kids you can still do that." 
</P>
<P>
At Carrow's Restaurant in Santa Paula one night last week, the Kolbeck kids -- 
two boys, four girls, ages 9, 7, 5, 4, 2 and 1 -- clustered around their 
parents while waiting for a table. 
</P>
<P>
"How many highchairs?" the hostess asked. 
</P>
<P>
One for baby Daniel was enough, but Michael, the oldest of the children, 
dutifully fetched booster seats for his two youngest sisters, Leah and Rebecca. 
The others are Sarah and Rachael. 
</P>
<P>
After placing orders -- mostly $1.99 entrees from the kids' menu -- the family 
talked about such things as what happened at school that day, their dog and two 
cats and the untimely demise of a pet rabbit. 
</P>
<P>
"You never have anything lacking to discuss when you have this many children," 
Michelle said. 
</P>
<P>
"My dad was something of a disciplinarian," Kevin said, explaining his own 
philosophy of fatherhood. "He wanted kids to be courteous to others and one 
another." 
</P>
<P>
Kevin and Michelle grew up in Iowa. He was the oldest and only boy among five 
children. Michelle was one of six. 
</P>
<P>
Kevin said he toyed with the idea of becoming a priest. "Then I saw my vocation 
was with the family," he said. 
</P>
<P>
"It made a difference in dating and courtship," he said. "I was looking for a 
certain type of spouse. Most of the women thought I was crazy. They'd say, 'you 
want to have how many kids?' " 
</P>
<P>
Michelle said that was more or less her reaction. 
</P>
<P>
"He came into this relationship knowing what he wanted," she said. "I thought 
it was very strange at first, because I was going to be this big career 
person." 
</P>
<P>
Michelle does have a job as a merchandiser for General Foods. Two to four 
nights a week, she visits grocery stores to make sure that the company's 
products are properly displayed. 
</P>
<P>
"I move Jell-O around," she said. 
</P>
<P>
"I know what my career is. It's raising six children." 
</P>
<P>
Her seventh is due in October -- one of the remaining six months when none of 
the Kolbeck children have birthdays. (The other open months are January, March, 
April, June and November.) 
</P>
<P>
Michelle's flexible work schedule allows her to stay with the kids until Kevin 
arrives home from his teaching job at Thomas Aquinas College. 
</P>
<P>
"We hardly ever have baby-sitters," Michelle said. "Not for work, anyway." 
</P>
<P>
Their two incomes amount to about $40,000 a year, Michelle said. That's enough 
to make the payments on their three-bedroom house and buy a few extras, such as 
the stereo in the living room and the glass of Scotch that Kevin enjoys after 
work. 
</P>
<P>
But, Michelle said, "we certainly don't send the kids to first grade in L.A. 
Gear shoes." 
</P>
<P>
She said Kevin is "a very unique husband." 
</P>
<P>
"In some ways he's a better parent than I am," she said. "At least he was smart 
enough when he was young to know what's important in life." 
</P>
</TEXT>
