<HEADLINE>
<P>
AZUSA'S POLICE CHIEF MAY FINALLY GET POMONA POST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIKE WARD, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
POMONA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Police Department, without a permanent police chief since Richard Tefank 
was fired last September, may get a new chief this week. 
</P>
<P>
City Administrator Julio Fuentes said he will recommend that the City Council 
on Monday confirm his choice of Azusa Police Chief Lloyd Wood, 50, who has 28 
years' experience in law enforcement. 
</P>
<P>
Wood, who has been under consideration for the job since February, had insisted 
earlier that he would accept the appointment only with a long-term employment 
agreement. Wood said he has given up his insistence on a three-year agreement 
and will accept the appointment to serve at the pleasure of the city 
administrator and council. 
</P>
<P>
He said he decided to take the job without the security of an employment 
contract because it had become controversial and he wants the job. He said he 
wants the challenge of working with a larger department in a larger city. 
</P>
<P>
After nine years in Azusa, he said, "I've done everything I can do. There's no 
challenge anymore." He said the departure of Councilman C. L. (Clay) Bryant, 
ousted in a recall election earlier this month, had nothing to do with his 
decision. Bryant had opposed Wood for the chief's job. 
</P>
<P>
Fuentes said he will recommend that the council confirm the appointment of 
Wood, effective July 18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
