<HEADLINE>
<P>
PLATFORM; 
</P>
<P>
WE CAN'T HAVE THIS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVEN BRODY, president of the Republican Law Students Assn. of Western 
State University College of Law in Fullerton, favors a constitutional amendment 
banning flag burning. He told The Times: 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There are very few things left in the country that are considered sacred. Some 
things just need to be preserved. You're brought up to believe in God and 
country, and I think the best symbol of our nation is the American flag. 
</P>
<P>
There can't be any other way to go except a constitutional amendment. Leaving 
it up to the state legislatures, you're going to have the ACLU behind it, or 
the real liberal legislators -- people like Ted Kennedy, who are saying, "I 
don't personally believe in flag burning, but it's freedom of expression." 
</P>
<P>
I don't see what flag burning proves. It's just something that really grips 
you. We had to endure that when we had hostages in Iran. But to see it in our 
own back yard, and to have Americans burning the flag, it really turns my 
stomach. That's one thing that I would have thought that our country could 
stand behind and stand up and say, "No we can't have this, something's got to 
be done about it, we need a constitutional amendment." 
</P>
</TEXT>
