<HEADLINE>
<P>
PARADISE PRESERVED ; 
</P>
<P>
FILOLI, IN NORTHERN CALIFORNIA, IS A STEP BACK TO THE GOLDEN AGE OF LAVISH 
ESTATE GARDENS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROBERT SMAUS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
THE MOST ELEGANT PUBLIC GARDEN in the state is virtually unknown by Southern 
Californians. Located in Woodside, in an oak-speckled valley just south of San 
Francisco, it easily compares with the classic European gardens that inspired 
its design. Named Filoli, an acronym for "fight, love, live," by its Faustian 
builder, William B. Bourn Jr., the estate is now a property of the National 
Trust for Historic Preservation. Bourn had the good fortune to inherit a 
hard-rock gold mine and the foresight to invest in water -- thus controlling 
Northern California's two most valuable resources. Suitably financed, he set 
about building his country place in 1916. 
</P>
<P>
He had the perfect spot, at the head of his own Crystal Springs Reservoir, 
which supplies San Francisco with water. Willis Polk, the designer of San 
Francisco City Hall, did the grand Irish country house, and Bruce Porter, a 
painter and designer of stained-glass windows, laid out the gardens (one walled 
garden is planted to resemble a window at Chartres Cathedral). 
</P>
<P>
In 1937, Mrs. William P. Roth purchased the property. An avid and knowledgeable 
horticulturist, she was careful not to tamper with the original scheme. A crew 
of expert gardeners, most of them Italian (many were in their 60s and 70s by 
the time the garden was transferred to the Trust), kept the garden impeccably 
maintained. Filoli is now one of the few grand estate gardens from the Country 
Place Era (which began at the turn of the century and ended with the 
Depression) that still looks as it did. 
</P>
<P>
Walking through the gates takes one back to this golden age of lavish gardens. 
"When I first arrived, it was like stepping into 'Alice in Wonderland' or the 
'Secret Garden,' " recalls Lucy Tolmach, superintendent of the garden. "It was 
so charming and so well preserved." A rustic copse of olives softens the 
transition from native oak savanna to man-made landscape. Once inside, yews, 
hedges and brick walls assert their formality -- everything is prim and pruned. 
The gardens are laid out along classic Italian-French lines with a series of 
walks connecting enclosed spaces and the allees tying the parts together 
visually. As is a characteristic of the Country Place Era, borders are brimming 
with flowers in bloom, as they are most of the year (these photographs were 
taken last August). 
</P>
<P>
Tours of the gardens are conducted, by reservation only, Tuesday through 
Saturday. Dedicated gardeners might enjoy the self-guided tour on Friday, which 
allows time to study the plants (reservations not required). Admission: $8; no 
children under 12. Telephone (415) 364-2880, or write to Filoli, Canada Road, 
Woodside 94062. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, COLOR, At right: Plants intended to be architectural elements are being 
pruned to their original proportions -- here, bay laurel are whitewashed to 
prevent sunburn as they wait to re-sprout. New hedges of English box barely 
contain an exuberant mix of flowers. The idea is to restore the garden, not 
change it. At left: In the view across the Sunken Garden, olive trees have been 
clipped to look like paper snowflakes and work to contrast the formal with the 
natural. ; Photo, COLOR, In the Knot Garden, gray santolina and horehound are 
tied to crimson barberry with spikes of 'Hidcote' lavender. Lemon verbena 
lollipops anchor the corners. Espaliered pears grow against the yews in the 
background. ; Photo, COLOR, In the Knot Garden, gray santolina and horehound 
are tied to crimson barberry with spikes of 'Hidcote' lavender. Lemon verbena 
lollipops anchor the corners. Espaliered pears grow against the yews in the 
background. ; Photo, COLOR, Above: Rows of dark-green yews and gray-green 
olives frame the Sunken Garden. ; Photo, COLOR, At left: This perennial bed is 
filled in August with golden rudbeckia, a pale yellow rue, spikes of lavender 
Russian sage, the highly colored foliage of the 'Purpureus' variety of smoke 
tree and the dainty blossoms of a new coreopsis named 'Early Sunrise.' ; Photo, 
COLOR, Left: A row of recently restored yews, some of the 250 on the property, 
marches off into the distance. ; Photo, COLOR, Below: Beneath the terrace and 
its tightly clipped English boxwoods grows a warm mix of summer annuals 
including zinnias and the plume celosia, cooled by white salvia and nicotiana. 
Alex Verticoff 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
