<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRITIC'S PICKS: NOTEWORTHY FILMS, WITH MINI-REVIEWS BY TIMES CRITICS.; 
</P>
<P>
WHO'S THAT KNOCKING AT MY DOOR? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KEVIN THOMAS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Virtually a companion film to the subsequent "Mean Streets," Martin Scorsese's 
1968 debut feature takes us into the impacted world of Manhattan's Little 
Italy, in which Harvey Keitel (pictured, in his film debut) does a lot of 
hanging out and is steeped in a very Catholic Madonna-prostitute complex about 
women. Zina Bethune is the captivating woman who seems from another world -- 
one that Keitel struggles to grasp. (A&amp;E Monday at 1 p.m.) KEVIN THOMAS 
</P>
</TEXT>
