<HEADLINE>
<P>
DISGRUNTLED HOLLYWOOD MERCHANTS FORM ORGANIZATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOSH MEYER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hollywood merchants have formed their own business watch organization, in part 
to counter efforts by the Hollywood Chamber of Commerce to start a management 
program headed by a former deputy to City Councilman Michael Woo. 
</P>
<P>
At its first meeting recently, the Hollywood Boulevard District Improvement 
Assn. voted unanimously to oppose the chamber's efforts to organize merchants 
through a contract it awarded to former Woo aide Nina Greenberg. 
</P>
<P>
The chamber awarded the $56,000 contract to Greenberg without competitive 
bidding and with little notice or publicity. Besides organizing area 
businesses, Greenberg's job description includes organizing merchants to form 
an assessment district in which merchants would be charged for improved city 
services. 
</P>
<P>
The idea of such an assessment district outraged many local merchants at the 
meeting, who said they already pay for services through an existing Hollywood 
Boulevard District. 
</P>
<P>
The association issued a statement condemning the contract and the 
chamber-sponsored business watch group. It read, in part, that: "The gross 
neglect and deterioration of the (existing) Hollywood Boulevard District over 
so many years is so outrageously scandalous and economically threatening that 
immediate attention and cooperation is demanded from City Councilman (Woo's) 
office, the Community Redevelopment Agency of Los Angeles and the Hollywood 
Chamber of Commerce to address and act upon these issues." 
</P>
<P>
The grass-roots improvement association, which claims dozens of members, met 
again Thursday night to determine specific program objectives. The group said 
it wants to improve an area from La Brea Avenue to Gower Street, and from Yucca 
Street to Selma Avenue, encompassing the Hollywood Walk of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
Several of the organizers are members of the Project Area Committee, an elected 
citizens panel that Woo replaced as the advisory body to the city Community 
Redevelopment Agency's $922-million Hollywood redevelopment project. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the group appointed as the new CRA advisory body, the Hollywood 
Community Advisory Council, has changed the meeting times of its executive 
committee to increase community input. The meetings have been moved to the 
second Monday of each month at 6:30 p.m. at the Hollywood Senior Multi-Purpose 
Center, 6501 Fountain Ave. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA061790-0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 235081 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
June 17, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Real Estate; Part K; Page 19; Column 6; Real Estate Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
157 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
APPRAISER UNIT APPROVES MERGER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Members of the American Institute of Real Estate Appraisers havevoted by 76% to 
consolidate with the nation's other leading appraisal group, the Society of 
Real Estate Appraisers. 
</P>
<P>
The new organization will begin its operations Jan. 1 under the name Appraisal 
Institute. 
</P>
<P>
All existing professional designations from both organizations will be 
retained, but only the MAI and SRA designations, for general and residential 
appraisers, respectively, will be retained after Jan. 1, according to Ritch 
LeGrand, president of the Society of Real Estate Appraisers. 
</P>
<P>
The new Appraisal Institute will be headquartered in Chicago and will maintain 
a legislative office in Washington, D.C. 
</P>
<P>
A. Scruggs Love Jr., president of the American Institute of Real Estate 
Appraisers, said the merger will assure that "anticipated state appraiser 
(licensing) legislation meets the high standards necessary to provide . . . 
competent appraisal services." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
