<HEADLINE>
<P>
FALDO HAS TO LOOK FOR UNION LABEL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MAL FLORENCE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MEDINAH, Ill. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Britain's Nick Faldo pointed his putter in mock anger Saturday on the 17th 
green at a group picketing the U.S. Open just outside a fence at the Medinah 
Country Club. 
</P>
<P>
Faldo seemed annoyed by the noise the picketers were making but made his putt. 
</P>
<P>
Representative of the International Ladies Garment Workers Union are protesting 
the USGA's sale of merchandise manufactured by LaMode du Golf, which 
manufactures golf shirts and other items. 
</P>
<P>
Union members also picketed the Bob Hope tournament at La Quinta in February. 
</P>
<P>
The USGA has terminated its contract with LaMode, a Los Angeles-based firm, 
effective July 31. 
</P>
<P>
The ILGWU has claimed that the USGA is LaMode's principal customer. The USGA 
disputes this claim, saying that its business accounts for less than 4% of 
LaMode sales. MAL FLORENCE 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Nick Faldo 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
DEMONSTRATIONS -- ILLINOIS; INTERNATIONAL LADIES GARMENT WORKERS UNION; LAMODE 
