<HEADLINE>
<P>
CLEANER GAS: IS IT CLEAN ENOUGH?; 
</P>
<P>
ENVIRONMENT: OIL FIRMS HAVE SCRAMBLED TO BRING OUT LOWER-EMISSION FUELS. BUT 
STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATORS WANT THEM TO GO FURTHER. THE INDUSTRY SAYS THE 
PRICE WILL BE HIGH, THE SUPPLY IN JEOPARDY. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PATRICK LEE, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Oil refiners are in a drag race for the public's gasoline dollars, but the flag 
they're after isn't checkered. It's green. 
</P>
<P>
Oil companies that once sold high octane, drivability or detergent additives 
are now touting fuels that burn cleaner and produce less smog. 
</P>
<P>
Last week Chevron Corp. became the latest of eight oil companies to introduce a 
lower-emission gasoline since Atlantic Richfield Co. started the trend last 
September with its EC-1 gasoline. 
</P>
<P>
Just how clean are these new fuels? Not as clean as they probably will have to 
be. And just how far is the oil industry willing to go in producing cleaner 
gasoline? Apparently, not much farther than it already has. 
</P>
<P>
Ultimately, the question may become: How clean can we make gasoline and how 
much are we willing to pay for it? 
</P>
<P>
The oil companies hope to sell more gasoline by exploiting growing 
environmental awareness among consumers. But as Congress and the California Air 
Resources Board contemplate stricter clean air rules, the oil companies also 
want to demonstrate that gasoline should be the cleaner-burning fuel of the 
future. 
</P>
<P>
Arco's EC-1 may have helped boost gasoline atop the agenda of lower-emissions 
fuels, displacing methanol, ethanol and compressed natural gas as the clean 
fuel of choice among federal regulators. "We didn't come out with EC-1 to 
increase share of market but to increase share of mind," said George H. 
Babikian, president of Arco Products Co. in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
So far, however, none of the new gasolines would satisfy all the proposed 
regulations before Congress or the state air resources board. 
</P>
<P>
EC-1 comes closest. Others, such as Shell SU 2000E, Chevron Supreme Unleaded 
and Exxon Plus, differ only slightly from ordinary gasolines. Others fall 
somewhere in between. Phillips, Conoco, Marathon and Diamond Shamrock are also 
selling reduced-emissions gasoline in various parts of the country, and Amoco, 
Sun and Citgo are considering bringing out their own reformulated gasolines 
soon. 
</P>
<P>
All the new gasolines are being sold in tightly restricted markets, reflecting 
the limited ability of oil refiners to produce them. The fuels are being made 
by juggling components from other gasolines -- and refiners can take that only 
so far without making major investments in new refining equipment. 
</P>
<P>
That may underlie the oil industry's opposition to new gasoline formulations 
proposed for a revised federal Clean Air Act. 
</P>
<P>
Despite its rush to sell lower-emissions fuels, the oil industry -- led by its 
main trade group, the American Petroleum Institute -- lobbied hard but 
unsuccessfully against the proposed Congressional formulas, which it derisively 
called "Government Gas." 
</P>
<P>
The API estimated that the new regulations would require $10 billion to $30 
billion in capital expenditures by refiners, forcing up to one-third of them 
out of business. The new rules would mean retail prices could be higher by 10 
to 15 cents per gallon and could even lead to gasoline shortages, the institute 
claimed. 
</P>
<P>
The industry would prefer that Congress set targets for auto emission 
reductions rather than specify gasoline formulas. It would be more efficient 
and less costly to let refiners then devise their own formulas to meet the 
targets, the industry argues. 
</P>
<P>
It also wants regulators to await the results of a multimillion-dollar joint 
research project being conducted by the oil and auto industries on various 
formulations of gasoline before settling on a formula. Those results won't be 
ready until year-end. 
</P>
<P>
But air quality officials insist on specific standards. 
</P>
<P>
"There's no other way to regulate the actual emissions from fuel, because there 
can be a variety of cars that would use it," said state Air Resources Board 
spokesman Bill Sessa. At issue are the proposed changes in the federal Clean 
Air Act contained in bills approved by the U.S. Senate in April and the House 
of Representatives last month. The bills differ in a number of ways, but both 
would mandate changes in the way gasoline is refined. A final version of the 
revisions must be hammered out in a conference committee. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the state Air Resources Board staff is developing proposals for 
reformulated gasoline. The board is supposed to vote on them in September. 
Where federal and state regulations overlap, the state board's rules would take 
precedence. Unlike Congress, the state is also contemplating rules that would 
require the use of alternative fuels beyond gasoline. 
</P>
<P>
The proposed rules would be among the most sweeping since state and federal 
governments began dictating what goes into gasoline. California led the way in 
the 1970s by setting limits on vapor pressure, or the tendency of gasoline to 
evaporate. It later required the phase-out of lead, a toxic substance linked to 
learning disorders in children. 
</P>
<P>
Since then, other states that once regulated only octane have begun to set 
standards for gasoline components. 
</P>
<P>
The federal government got into the act later. In 1975, it followed California 
in requiring the phase-out of lead nationwide, perhaps the biggest change in 
the refining of gasoline until now. Just last year, the U.S. Environmental 
Protection Agency set national standards for vapor pressure. 
</P>
<P>
"We have gone through major sea changes in the required chemical composition of 
gasoline over our history," said industry analyst Bernard J. Picchi at Salomon 
Bros. in New York. "Perhaps the most dramatic switch was the change from leaded 
to unleaded gasoline, and I think that was actually a more wrenching change for 
the industry than what is being contemplated here -- and that transition took 
place without there being a major dislocation." 
</P>
<P>
In contrast to the API, the EPA estimates the added cost to consumers of the 
new gas rules will be only 5 to 10 cents per gallon. Moreover, the API's 
$10-billion to $30-billion capital estimate is high, critics argue. 
</P>
<P>
The Bush Administration puts the cost of the entire clean air law -- not just 
provisions dealing with reformulated gasoline -- at just $21.5 billion. 
</P>
<P>
There is also disagreement over what effects the House and Senate versions of 
the Clean Air Act would have. 
</P>
<P>
Both bills would require the addition beginning in 1992 of high levels of 
oxygenates to gasoline sold in the nine smoggiest U.S. cities, including Los 
Angeles. More oxygenates would promote more efficient burning and reduce 
certain emissions, proponents argue. 
</P>
<P>
Both bills would also make refiners reduce aromatics and benzene, the most 
polluting components of gasoline. (Unlike the Senate bill, the House bill gives 
refiners flexibility on gasoline formulation, if they can meet or exceed 
emissions standards.) 
</P>
<P>
"The legislation passed by the House sets extremely stringent standards for 
reformulated gasoline," said Charles J. DiBona, president of API. 
</P>
<P>
He added in a statement: "Unless substantial changes are made in this 
legislation by a House-Senate conference committee, it may not be possible for 
the industry to continue to meet the fuel needs of consumers." 
</P>
<P>
Among other things, API argued that there is a significant shortage of a key 
oxygenate, methyl tertiary butyl ether, or MTBE. Lower-emissions gasolines now 
on the market all contain MTBE, but generally at less than half the levels that 
would be required by 1994. 
</P>
<P>
Critics of the oil industry argue that refiners are less worried about higher 
costs or fuel shortages than they are about losing control of what goes into 
the nation's gasoline pool -- and giving up some of the attendant profits. 
</P>
<P>
By requiring higher levels of oxygenates, Congress will force refiners to go to 
outside sources for the chemicals if they can't make enough themselves. 
</P>
<P>
If the oxygenate is MTBE, that would mean eventually relinquishing control of 
15% of the gasoline pool. Some of that business would undoubtedly go to foreign 
manufacturers. 
</P>
<P>
If refiners are forced to rely on ethanol, it would mean a sizable increase in 
business for Archer Daniels Midland, the agriculture conglomerate that produces 
about 45% of the nation's ethanol. 
</P>
<P>
Critics also argue that API has exaggerated the disruption that would result 
from the new rules. 
</P>
<P>
Even some refiners admit privately that they can accommodate the requirements 
of the proposed clean air bills, though they may not like having to shell out 
the capital investments. 
</P>
<P>
"Nobody likes to be forced to make dramatic changes that aren't kind of 
market-driven and that you have time to work into," said David Kem, general 
manager of marketing in North America for Conoco Inc. in Houston. "But this 
industry has adapted to other things, and I think it will adapt to this." 
</P>
<P>
"I do not think it is going to result in the closure of refineries; in fact, I 
would argue just the opposite," Picchi said. "As a result of the new higher 
level of capital spending required to retool refineries . . . , you'll probably 
see refiners at the same time taking advantage of the situation to spend more 
money to expand capacity." 
</P>
<P>
That's because the clean air requirements could make it easier to get permits 
that might otherwise be hard-won, particularly in environmentally sensitive 
areas such as Los Angeles, he said. 
</P>
<P>
Atlantic Richfield, for one, is planning to expand gasoline-making capacity at 
its refineries in Carson and Cherry Point, Wash., at the same time that it 
retools to make more reformulated gasoline. 
</P>
<P>
In the next five years, Arco plans to spend $1.1 billion at the refineries to 
make reformulated gasoline. After that, it will spend $1 billion to $1.3 
billion to meet future requirements for the fuel. 
</P>
<P>
Shell, the nation's largest gasoline marketer, which introduced a reformulated 
gasoline in April in the nine smoggiest cities, is studying upgrades at six of 
its seven refineries -- a process that will take years and cost billions. 
</P>
<P>
MTBE capacity nationally is about 100,000 barrels per day, well short of the 
289,000 barrels expected to be needed for gasoline consumed in the nine 
smoggiest cities as required under the proposed revisions, said Roy Sugimoto, a 
researcher with the consulting firm DeWitt &amp; Co. in Houston, which tracks 
MTBE projects. 
</P>
<P>
But 110,000 barrels per day of new capacity is already planned, and 
construction on several plants could begin within the next year or two at an 
average cost of $160 million to $180 million per plant, he said. 
</P>
<P>
Tenneco is planning one of the new MTBE plants -- a 12,500-barrel-per-day 
facility to be completed in the spring of 1992. 
</P>
<P>
"We are aware of an additional five to six projects of similar size now being 
planned in the industry and expect that between eight and twelve projects could 
be built in the United States by 1994 to meet growing octane and clean-air 
demands," Tenneco executive Michael Falco wrote in a letter to Sen. Thomas A. 
Daschle, the South Dakota Democrat who co-wrote the Senate amendment. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it's too early to say whether any of the existing reformulated 
gasolines is taking its market by storm. But early signs are that the fuels are 
winning some public acceptance. 
</P>
<P>
Arco says EC-1, being sold in the Los Angeles area to former customers of its 
leaded regular gasoline, has been gaining market share slowly each month and 
now accounts for about a third of the leaded regular market in Southern 
California. 
</P>
<P>
That performance is particularly good given that the regular leaded market is 
declining, Arco's Babikian said. 
</P>
<P>
Have the new gasolines had a measurable effect on air quality? Again, it's too 
soon to tell. California air quality officials confirm Arco's claims that EC-1 
would cut pollutants from older cars by about 20%. But clean-air advocates 
agree that the current reformulated gasolines are only a first step. 
</P>
<P>
"We have no idea how clean you can make a refined petroleum product," said 
David Hawkins, senior attorney with the Natural Resources Defense Council, an 
environmental group. "And I'm not sure the industry has any idea either." 
</P>
